#--------First i generated a categorical variables because i dont have them 
#--------Generate A Categorical Variable
screen_weight_cut= cut(HW_Data$screen_weight, breaks = c(0, 5, 10, 15, 20))
HW_Data$Category[HW_Data$screen_weight>=0 &HW_Data$screen_weight<5] = "too Heavy"
HW_Data$Category[HW_Data$screen_weight>=5 &HW_Data$screen_weight <10] = "Heavy"
HW_Data$Category[HW_Data$screen_weight>=10 &HW_Data$screen_weight<15] = "Better"
HW_Data$Category[HW_Data$screen_weight>=15 &HW_Data$screen_weight<=20] = "light weight"
Category_Screen_Weight=as.factor(HW_Data$Category)


screen_height_cut= cut(HW_Data$screen_height, breaks = c(4,8 ,12, 16, 20))
HW_Data$HCategory[HW_Data$screen_height>=4 &HW_Data$screen_height<8] = "Very_Small"
HW_Data$HCategory[HW_Data$screen_height>=8 &HW_Data$screen_height <12] = "Small"
HW_Data$HCategory[HW_Data$screen_height>=12 &HW_Data$screen_height<16] = "Medium"
HW_Data$HCategory[HW_Data$screen_height>=16 &HW_Data$screen_height<=20] = "Large"
Category_Screen_Height=as.factor(HW_Data$HCategory)


Talk_time_cut= cut(HW_Data$talk_time, breaks = c(0, 4, 8, 16, 20))
HW_Data$Talk.Category[HW_Data$talk_time>=0 &HW_Data$talk_time<4] = "not enough"
HW_Data$Talk.Category[HW_Data$talk_time>=4 &HW_Data$talk_time<8] = "enough"
HW_Data$Talk.Category[HW_Data$talk_time>=8 &HW_Data$talk_time<12] = "Normal"
HW_Data$Talk.Category[HW_Data$talk_time>=12 &HW_Data$talk_time<=20] = "High_Time"
Category_talk_Time=as.factor(HW_Data$Talk.Category)


Primary_Cam_cut= cut(HW_Data$primry_cam, breaks = c(0, 5, 10, 15, 20))
HW_Data$Camera.Category[HW_Data$primry_cam>=0 &HW_Data$primry_cam<5] = "bad"
HW_Data$Camera.Category[HW_Data$primry_cam>=5 &HW_Data$primry_cam<10] = "Fine"
HW_Data$Camera.Category[HW_Data$primry_cam>=10 &HW_Data$primry_cam<15] = "Good"
HW_Data$Camera.Category[HW_Data$primry_cam>=15 &HW_Data$primry_cam<=20] = "Exceptional"
Category_Primary_Cam=as.factor(HW_Data$Camera.Category)
Data_HW=cbind(HW_Data$Category,HW_Data$HCategory,HW_Data$Talk.Category,HW_Data$Camera.Category)
Screen_Weight=Data_HW[,1]
Screen_Height=Data_HW[,2]
contingency_table = table(Screen_Weight,Screen_Height) # contingency table creation

library(FactoMineR)
library(factoextra)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
Hw.ca=CA(contingency_table, graph =F)  # simple correspondence analysis 

Hw.ca=CA(contingency_table, graph =T) #  a correspondence map

fviz_ca_biplot(Hw.ca, repel = T, map = "rowprincipal") # an asymmetric map - rows (Screen weight)

fviz_ca_biplot(Hw.ca, repel = T, map = "columnprincipal") # an asymmetric map - rows (Scree Height)

fviz_ca_biplot(Hw.ca, repel = T)

the axes or quadrants of the map shows the dimensions If we sum up the proportion of variance explained by horizontal and vertical dimensions (shown in the axis labels),we see that visualization displays 94% of the variance in the data, which is really good number. So, a lot of the data is a part of the summary.

## **Results of the Multiple Correspondence Analysis (MCA)**

## *The results are available in the following objects:
## 
##    name                description                                          
## 1  "$eig"              "eigenvalues"                                        
## 2  "$var"              "results for the variables"

## 4  "$var$cos2"         "cos2 for the categories"                            
## 5  "$var$contrib"      "contributions of the categories"
